## (5)(b) Pathloss and Eb/N0 Calculation

> Calculate the pathloss (L_dB) and the Eb/N0 of a WiFi system (IEEE 802.11e).
>
> Given: $h_t$ = 0.1 m, $h_r$ = 2 m, 8 kbits/sample at 1000 samples/sec, $k$ = 1.3803 × 10⁻²³ J/K, BW = 20 MHz, T = 300 K *(15 marks)*

---

### Step 1: Calculate Data Rate

$$R_b = 8000 \text{ bits/sample} \times 1000 \text{ samples/sec} = 8 \text{ Mbps}$$

---

### Step 2: Pathloss (Two-Ray Ground Model)

**Given:** $h_t = 0.1$ m, $h_r = 2$ m, assume $d = 100$ m

$$L_{dB} = 40\log_{10}(d) - 20\log_{10}(h_t \cdot h_r)$$

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
L_{dB} &= 40\log_{10}(100) - 20\log_{10}(0.1 \times 2) \\
&= 40 \times 2 - 20\log_{10}(0.2) \\
&= 80 - 20 \times (-0.699) \\
&= 80 + 13.98 \\
&= 93.98 \text{ dB}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

> **Pathloss: $L_{dB} = 94$ dB**

---

### Step 3: Received Power

Assuming transmit power $P_t = 100$ mW (20 dBm, typical WiFi):

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
P_r &= P_t - L_{dB} \\
&= 20 - 94 \\
&= -74 \text{ dBm} \\
&= -104 \text{ dBW}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

---

### Step 4: $E_b/N_0$ Calculation (shortcut formula)

$$\frac{E_b}{N_0} (dB) = P_r (dBW) - 10\log_{10}(R_b) - 10\log_{10}(k) - 10\log_{10}(T)$$

<div class="math-left">

$$\begin{aligned}
\frac{E_b}{N_0} &= -104 - 10\log_{10}(8 \times 10^6) - 10\log_{10}(1.38 \times 10^{-23}) - 10\log_{10}(300) \\
&= -104 - 69.03 + 228.6 - 24.77 \\
&= 30.8 \text{ dB}
\end{aligned}$$

</div>

> **$E_b/N_0 = 30.8$ dB**
